Backgrounder: Major events in China-U.S. military ties since 2008
2011-01-19 07:16:55 GMT
BEIJING, Oct. 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Liang Guanglie held talks with his U.S. counterpart Robert Gates in Hanoi on Monday on the sidelines of a meeting of defense ministers from the Association of Southeastern Asian Nations and partners countries.Following are major events in China-U.S. military ties since 2008.Jan. 13-16, 2008 -- Commander-in-Chief of the U.S. Pacific Command Timothy Keating paid a four-day visit to China, during which he met with senior Chinese army and government officials, including Vice Chairman of the Central Military Commission Guo Boxiong, Chinese Chief of General Staff Chen Bingde and Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi.Feb. 28-29, 2008 -- Officials of the defense ministries of China and the United States meet in Shanghai. The two sides signed an agreement on setting up a military hotline between the two defense departments and an agreement on launching military archives cooperation in order to find U.S. military personnel missing in the 1950-1953 Korean War.April 10, 2008 -- Chinese Defense Minister Liang Guanglie and U.S. Defense Secretary Robert Gates held their first phone conversation.Liang expressed the hope that the United States will abide by its repeated commitments to adhere to the one-China policy and the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques. He urged the United States to cease arms sales and military links with Taiwan in a bid to maintain peace and stability across the Taiwan Strait and safeguard the overall interests of Sino-U.S. relations.Oct. 3, 2008 -- The U.S. government announced plans to sell a massive arms package to Taiwan, including 30 Apache attack helicopters and 330 Patriot missiles.China cut some military exchanges with the United States following Washington's approval of the 6.5-billion-dollar arms package for Taiwan.April 1, 2009 -- Chinese President Hu Jintao held his first face-to-face talk with his U.S. counterpart Barack Obama in London. Both sides reaffirmed their commitments to military-to-military relations and vowed to work for their continued improvement and development.June 23-24, 2009 -- The 10th round of Sino-U.S. defense consultations were held in Beijing, the highest-level defense dialogue between the two countries since the inception of the Obama administration.Oct. 24-Nov. 3, 2009 -- Vice Chairman of China's Central Military Commission Xu Caihou paid an official visit to the United States.Jan. 30, 2010 -- Washington announced a 6.4-billion-dollar arms sale package for Taiwan, which includes Patriot missiles, Black Hawk helicopters and minesweepers, communications equipment for Taiwan's fleet of F-16 fighter jets, among other weaponry. China lodged a solemn protest over the arms sale. 
